.SH "NAME"
odgi_matrix \- write the graph topology in sparse matrix formats
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBodgi matrix\fP [\fB\-i, \-\-idx\fP=\fIFILE\fP] [\fIOPTION\fP]...
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
The odgi matrix(1) command generates a sparse matrix format out of the graph topology of a given variation graph.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.SS "Graph Files IO"
.sp
\fB\-i, \-\-idx\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
File containing the succinct variation graph to create the sparse matrix from. The file name usually ends with \fI.og\fP.
.RE
.SS "Matrix Options"
.sp
\fB\-e, \-\-edge\-depth\-weight\fP
.RS 4
Weigh edges by their path depth.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-d, \-\-delta\-weight\fP
.RS 4
Weigh edges by their inverse id delta.
.RE
.SS "Program Information"
.sp
\fB\-h, \-\-help\fP
.RS 4
Print a help message for \fBodgi matrix\fP.
.RE
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.sp
\fB0\fP
.RS 4
Success.
.RE
.sp
\fB1\fP
.RS 4
